 egin{remark} The weight-based strategy has been applied to more general networks than considered in the present survey. For example,   and  use a similar scheme to detect communities in {\it multi-layer} networks. Another example is
SANS  that works with {\it directed} node-attributed graphs. 
Edge weighting similar to (ef{main_weight}) is also applied in FocusCO	. Although it is not a purely unsupervised community detection method (it requires user's preferences on some of the attributes), it can simultaneously extract local clusters and detect outliers in a node-attributed social network.
\end{remark}
 egin{remark}
Let us mention that there exist community detection methods similar ideologically (attributes $	o$ edge weights $	o$ weighted graph node embeddings ootnote{Low-dimensional continuous vector representations of graph nodes. See also Subsection~ef{class-ef-embedding}.} $	o$ $k$-means) but preceding to recently proposed { f AA-Cluster} . Namely, GraphEncoder~ and  GraRep~  also first convert a node-attributed graph into a weighted one according to (ef{main_weight}) with $\alpha=0$ and then find corresponding node embeddings. The embeddings are further fed to $k$-means algorithm to detect communities. However, in opposite to ,  and   mostly focus on node embedding techniques for a weighted graph than on the community detection task. 
\end{remark}

