Methods from this subclass (see Table~\ref{tab:agent}) treat a node-attributed social network as a dynamic system and assume that its community structure is a consequence of certain interactions among nodes (of course, the attributes are thought to affect the interactions). Some of the methods assume that the interactions occur in an information propagation process, i.e. while information is sent to or received from every node. Others comprehend each node as an autonomous agent and develop a multi-agent system to detect communities. Note that these approaches are rather recent and consider community detection in node-attributed social networks from a new perspective. Furthermore, they seem to be efficient for large networks as can be easily parallelized.
